articles.author: Ron Bousso
articles.description: Shell (SHEL.L) will cut around 15% of its low-carbon division workforce and scale back its hydrogen business as part of CEO Wael Sawan's drive to boost profits, the company told Reuters on Wednesday.
articles.title: Exclusive: Shell cuts low carbon jobs, scales back hydrogen in CEO overhaul -sources

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Honda Motor (7267.T) and General Motors (GM.N) are scrapping plans to jointly develop affordable electric vehicles (EVs), a Honda spokesperson said on Wednesday, confirming a Bloomberg News report.
articles.title: Honda, GM scrap plan to co-develop cheaper EVs

articles.author: Jonathan Stempel
articles.description: Consumer Reports on Wednesday said it has found "concerning" levels of lead and cadmium in a new array of chocolate products, and renewed its call for Hershey (HSY.N) to reduce the amounts of heavy metals its chocolate contains.
articles.title: Consumer Reports finds more lead, cadmium in chocolate, urges change at Hershey

articles.author: Jody Godoy
articles.description: Sam Bankman-Fried has little to lose by bucking conventional wisdom and taking the stand at his criminal fraud trial, following weeks of testimony that he stole billions of dollars from unwitting customers of his FTX cryptocurrency exchange.
articles.title: Sam Bankman-Fried might risk testifying in criminal trial, experts say

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: The United States is ready to help Vietnam in preparing auctions for rare earths mines, the U.S. State Department chief economist Emily Blanchard on Wednesday.
articles.title: US says ready to help Vietnam with rare earth auctions

articles.author: Pete Schroeder
articles.description: The U.S. Federal Reserve is expected on Wednesday to propose an official review of the fees banks can charge retailers for debit card transactions, setting up a battle between the two industries that could result in a court challenge.
articles.title: US Fed set to revise debit card fee caps pitting banks against retailers

articles.author: Corina Pons, Helen Reid
articles.description: Zara owner Inditex (ITX.MC), the world's biggest clothing retailer, has agreed to invest in and buy recycled polyester from U.S. start-up Ambercycle, according to a document seen by Reuters.
articles.title: Zara owner Inditex invests in US polyester recycling start-up

articles.author: Nidal Al-Mughrabi, Emily Rose
articles.description: Countries including the United States, Canada, Russia and Arab states pushed for either a pause or ceasefire in fighting between Israel and Hamas in the Gaza Strip so that humanitarian aid could be delivered to besieged Palestinian civilians, and late on Tuesday eight trucks with water, food and medicine entered the enclave from Egypt.
articles.title: World leaders seek to suspend Israel-Hamas fighting for Gaza aid

articles.author: Aditya Soni
articles.description: Microsoft is outstripping Alphabet in the race to make money from generative artificial intelligence through early bets on OpenAI and focus on big clients, raising worries that the Google parent could lose share in the cloud-computing market.
articles.title: Microsoft surpasses Alphabet in cloud race with OpenAI bet, enterprise focus

articles.author: Trevor Hunnicutt
articles.description: Alphabet's Google (GOOGL.O) will run undersea cables powering internet access to at least eight far-flung Pacific Ocean nations under a joint U.S.-Australian deal set to be announced on Wednesday, according to a U.S. official.
articles.title: Exclusive: Google to run internet cables to Pacific islands in Australia-US deal
